"policy_citations":[
{
"source":"aml_thresholds.md",
"text":"## Typologies to detect\n- **Structuring / smurfing:** multiple deposits kept **just under INR 50,000** to avoid\n  reporting, often across several accounts that funnel to one beneficiary within days.\n- **Layering (circular transfers):** funds moved through a chain of accounts (A\u2192B\u2192C\u2192A)\n  to obscure origin, with little economic substance.\n- **Shared-device / linked-identity rings:** multiple ostensibly unrelated accounts\n  transacting from the **same device or IP** in a short window.",
"score":0.3
},
{
"source":"aml_thresholds.md",
"text":"## Reporting thresholds\n- **Cash Transaction Report (CTR):** aggregate cash transactions exceeding **INR 10,00,000**\n  in a month for a single account must be reviewed.\n- **Suspicious Transaction Report (STR):** file when activity has no apparent lawful\n  purpose or economic rationale, regardless of amount.",
"score":0.038
},
{
"source":"aml_thresholds.md",
"text":"## Risk factors\n- Customer is a **PEP** or in a high-risk occupation.\n- Counterparty in a high-risk jurisdiction or flagged by sanctions screening.\n- Velocity: many transactions in a short window inconsistent with KYC profile.",
"score":-0.055
}
],
"str_narrative":"Subject: Suspicious Transaction Report (STR)\n\nThe investigation revealed a suspicious transaction pattern characteristic of Shared-device / linked-identity rings typology. On Device ID DEV-RING-001, multiple ostensibly unrelated accounts ACC-DEV-01 through ACC-DEV-08 performed circular transactions with minimal economic substance, citing object_ids TXN-R00093, TXN-R00097, and TXN-R00104 as examples of such transactions. Specifically, funds were transferred in a loop among these accounts (e.g., ACC-DEV-01 to ACC-DEV-02 to ACC-DEV-03 back to ACC-DEV-01) through the linked-device, with no apparent lawful purpose. This activity closely resembles the Layering (circular transfers) typology and may be indicative of an attempt to obscure origin. The lack of economic substance and frequent circular transactions among these accounts suggest a potentially illicit financial practice in accordance with the bank's established policies.\n\nIt is proposed that this issue be addressed through escalating to a case, as it warrants further human analysis due to its suspicious nature and potential compliance implications.",
"source":"cached"
},
